== Introduction: Don't Fear the Commune!

Hello and welcome to ExpatsatHome! My name is Laurine. I was born and raised in Belgium, and now I'm an expat myself. I understand that feeling of excitement mixed with a little bit of anxiety when you move to a new country. And in Belgium, one word often stands out as a source of that anxiety: the *commune* (or *gemeente* in Dutch).

You’ve probably heard stories of long queues, confusing paperwork, and strict officials. It can feel like a daunting first hurdle in your new Belgian life.

But I'm here to tell you not to worry. This guide is designed to be your friendly local expert, walking you through the entire process step-by-step. We'll demystify the jargon, clarify the deadlines, and give you the insider tips you need to make your registration as smooth and stress-free as possible. By the end of this guide, you won't just survive your commune visit—you'll master it.

Let's begin!

== Chapter 1: First Things First - Deadlines & Appointments

Before you start gathering documents, you need to understand the two most critical first steps: your registration deadline and how to get an appointment. Getting this right is half the battle.

=== Know Your Deadline: The Most Important Rule

The Belgian government is very strict about registration deadlines. Missing yours can lead to complications, so pay close attention. The deadline depends entirely on your citizenship.

#warning-box[
  *CRITICAL DEADLINES* \
  - *EU/EEA Citizens*: You must register within *three (3) months* of your arrival in Belgium. \
  - *Non-EU Citizens*: You must register within *eight (8) working days* of your arrival in Belgium. This is extremely important and not flexible.
]

This is the single most important rule in the entire process. Mark the date on your calendar, set a reminder on your phone—do whatever you need to do to ensure you book your appointment well within this timeframe.

=== Booking Your Appointment: Goodbye, 5 AM Queues!

Thankfully, the days of waking up before dawn to stand in a line outside the commune are mostly over. For expats in the Brussels-Capital Region, the process has been streamlined through a central online portal.

*IRISbox: Your Digital Gateway*

For all 19 communes in Brussels, the primary way to book an appointment is through the #link("https://irisbox.irisnet.be/irisbox/", "IRISbox") platform. This is the official electronic service counter for the region.

#info-box(title: "How to Use IRISbox")[
  1.  *Visit the Website*: Go to the IRISbox homepage.
  2.  *Select Your Commune*: Choose your local commune from the dropdown list.
  3.  *Find the Service*: Look for "Registration for Foreigners" or a similar service. The exact wording might vary slightly.
  4.  *Choose a Timeslot*: The system will show you available dates and times. Select one that works for you.
  5.  *Confirm*: You will receive a confirmation email with your appointment details. Save this email!
]

#tip-box[
  Book your appointment as soon as you have your rental contract signed. Appointment slots can fill up quickly, especially during peak moving seasons (like late summer). Don't wait until the last minute!
]

If you live outside of Brussels, check your specific commune's website (*site web de la commune* / *website van de gemeente*). Most now offer online booking systems, but some smaller towns may still require a phone call or an in-person visit to book.

