== Chapter 3: The Step-by-Step Registration Journey

Now that you have your appointment and understand the terminology, let's walk through the entire process from start to finish.

=== Step 1: The First Appointment at the Commune

This is the main event. You've prepared your documents (see the checklist in the next chapter!), you have your appointment confirmation, and you're ready to go.

*What to Expect:*
- *Arrive Early*: Plan to arrive 10-15 minutes before your scheduled time.
- *Check-in*: You'll likely need to check in at a reception desk or a digital kiosk. You'll be given a ticket number.
- *Wait Patiently*: Even with an appointment, there's often a bit of a wait. Bring a book or have a podcast ready. Plan for the entire visit to take 60-90 minutes.
- *Meet the Official*: When your number is called, you'll go to the designated counter (*guichet*). The official will ask for your documents. Hand over your entire prepared file. They will review everything, scan your documents, and enter your details into the national register.
- *Get Your First Documents*: At the end of this appointment, you will receive your first official Belgian documents. For an EU citizen, this is often the *Annexe 19*. For a non-EU citizen, it might be the *Déclaration d'arrivée*. Most importantly, you will be assigned and given your *National Number (NISS)*.

#warning-box[
  Your *National Number (NISS)* is your key to life in Belgium. Guard it carefully. Take a photo of the document it's printed on as soon as you receive it. You'll need it almost immediately to open a bank account or set up health insurance.
]

=== Step 2: The Police Visit (Don't Panic!)

This part of the process often sounds alarming to newcomers, but it's a completely normal and routine procedure in Belgium called the *contrôle de résidence*.

*The Purpose*: A local police officer (*agent de quartier*) will visit your home address simply to confirm that you actually live there. This is a measure to prevent "address fraud."

*How it Works*:
- The officer will come to your home, usually within a few weeks of your commune appointment. The timing can vary greatly.
- They will ring your doorbell.
- You open the door, they will see you, maybe ask for your ID to confirm your name, and that's it. They are not there to inspect your home or ask intrusive questions. The entire interaction typically lasts less than a minute.

#tip-box[
  *THE SINGLE MOST IMPORTANT TIP FOR A SMOOTH REGISTRATION:* \
  As soon as you move in, you *must* put your name on your doorbell and your mailbox. If the police officer arrives and your name isn't visible, they will assume you don't live there, file a negative report, and leave. This can delay your registration by weeks or even months. A simple piece of paper with your name taped on is enough to start!
]

=== Step 3: The Waiting Game & The Magic Letter

After the police have successfully verified your address, they send their confirmation back to the commune. Now, the final administrative processing begins.

The timeline from your first appointment to receiving your final residence card typically takes *two to three months*. This is a normal Belgian administrative timeline. Patience is a virtue you will quickly learn!

Eventually, you will receive a letter in the mail from the commune. This letter is very important. It will contain the PIN and PUK codes for your electronic residence card. This letter is your signal: your card is ready!

=== Step 4: Card Collection - The Final Step!

Once you have your PIN/PUK letter, you will usually need to book one last, quick appointment at the commune to pick up your residence card.

You will go to the commune, present your PIN/PUK letter and your ID, and they will give you your official Belgian residence card.
- *EU Citizens*: You'll receive the *E-Card*.
- *Non-EU Citizens*: You'll typically receive the *A-Card*.

Congratulations! You are now officially registered as a resident of Belgium.

